According to a report by Intel Market Research, the global Calcium Ammonium Nitrate (CAN) Market was valued at USD 5.24 billion in 2023 and is projected to decline from USD 5.11 billion in 2024 to USD 3.89 billion by 2032, registering a negative CAGR of 4.6% during the forecast period. Although the market is expected to contract due to the increasing adoption of precision farming practices and alternative high-efficiency fertilizers, Calcium Ammonium Nitrate continues to play a vital role in modern agriculture owing to its balanced nitrogen supply, improved nutrient absorption, and ability to enhance soil health. The fertilizer remains particularly valuable in regions with acidic soils and high rainfall, where its calcium content helps improve soil structure while minimizing nitrogen losses through volatilization.
The growing global demand for food production, coupled with the need to improve crop productivity on limited arable land, continues to support the use of CAN in commercial farming. Its unique combination of nitrate nitrogen for immediate plant uptake and ammonium nitrogen for sustained nutrient release makes it a preferred fertilizer for cereals, fruits, vegetables, and other high-value crops. Furthermore, governments in several agricultural economies are promoting balanced fertilizer application and soil nutrient management programs, encouraging farmers to adopt fertilizers that improve both crop yields and long-term soil fertility. Large-scale commercial farms are increasingly utilizing CAN due to its high nutrient efficiency, compatibility with precision agriculture technologies, and ability to optimize fertilizer application while reducing environmental losses.
